tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne hundred years after the publication of the great sociological treatise, The Elementary Forms of Religious Life, this new volume shows how aptly Durkheim¹s theories still resonate with the study of contemporary and historical religious societies. The volume applies the Durkheimian model to multiple cases, probing its resilience, wondering where it might be tweaked, and asking which aspects have best stood the test of time. A dialogue between theory and ethnography, this book shows how Durkheimian sociology has become a mainstay of social thought and theory, pointing to multiple ways in which Durkheim¹s work on religion remains relevant to our thinking about culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCults. 0aReligion. 0aRites and ceremonies. 0aTotemism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aAllen, N.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumann, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChau, Adam Yuet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChild, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFields, Karen E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamble, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausner, Sondra L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausner, Sondra L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Susan Stedman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, W. Watts, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichards, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https